Climate Report

Temperature and Precipitation 1960-2014

Christian Kim

5/10/2019

Data

The data we used was April 1960, 1986, and 2014. We use these dates because 1960 is the beginning of the data set, 1986 is the middle of the data set and 2014 is the last year in the data set. Each data set has a longitude, latitude, air temperature (celsius), time (date), and the percipitation (centimeters).

Temperature

1960 Airtemp of North America (Celsius)

1986 Airtemp of North America (Celsius)

2014 Airtemp of North America (Celsius)

The temperature patterns look reasonable. The further you go from the equater, the colder the airtemp and vice versa. There are not major differences between years. Only slight changes overall but over the 3 data sets it got slightly warmer in air temperature, especially in the USA and on the west side of Canada. However, in and around the area of Alaska, it warmed up over the three data points.

Precipitation

1960 Precipitation of North America (Centimeter)

1986 Precipitation of North America (Centimeter)

2014 Precipitation of North America (Centimeter)

The precipitation patterns look reasonable. There is the most rain near a body of water. There are major differences over the year. On the west coast from Washington up to Alaska, there is significantly less rain. There is also less rain in central and eastern USA, but there is more Rain on the southern side of Greenland.
